#compdef deviceframe dframe
# ============================================================================
# deviceframe / dframe - Frame your screenshots in device chrome (Node, MIT)
#
# Author : c0bra
# Upstream: https://github.com/c0bra/deviceframe
# npm    : deviceframe (binaries: deviceframe + dframe)
#
# `deviceframe` wraps an image (or a screenshot captured from a
# URL via headless puppeteer) in a device chrome - iPhone, iPad,
# Galaxy, MacBook, Apple Watch, etc. - so the final image
# matches the "phone-in-hand" product marketing aesthetic.
# Supports hundreds of devices via the deviceframe-frames
# bundle (separate repo + version-pinned via package.json).
# Resolves user input against the device list via fuzzy match
# so "iphone 7" matches "Apple iPhone 7" without exact-string
# matching.
#
# Same package ships two equivalent bins: `deviceframe` (long
# form) and `dframe` (short form).
#
# Inputs: any combination of local image files (globs ok),
# image URLs, or page URLs (rendered via puppeteer headless
# Chrome with a configurable delay).
#
# Flags (meow):
#       --delay <sec>     - delay webpage capture (seconds)
#   -o, --output <dir>    - output directory (default CWD)
#   -d, --debug           - log debug info
#       --devices         - list all available devices
#       --frame <name>    - select frame(s) by fuzzy match;
#                           repeatable or comma-separated
#   -h, --help            - print help
#
# The fuse.js lane is built on `fuse.js ^3.2.0` (declared
# verbatim at upstream package.json HEAD), the canonical
# Node fuzzy-string matcher by Kiro Risk (github.com/krisk/
# Fuse, 18000+ stars). fuse.js is the de-facto JS fuzzy
# library across the npm ecosystem - extensive Smith-Waterman-
# style scoring with weighted multi-key matching, token-based
# AND/OR queries, configurable threshold + distance +
# location bias, and the ability to return per-match indices
# for UI highlighting. deviceframe uses fuse.js to match the
# user-typed --frame arg ("iphone 7") against the >300 entries
# in the device list, returning the top-scoring frames for
# rendering.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 225 :: Fuzzy string matching (fzf-quality scoring + ranking)  [CLOSES]
# Round 1375 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 225 (218th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : helix-editor/nucleo          [R1373 _purple]
#   Go      : sahilm/fuzzy                 [R1374 _nidhi]
#   TS/Node : krisk/Fuse (fuse.js)         [R1375 THIS FILE]
#
# fuse.js diverges from the nucleo + sahilm/fuzzy lane in one
# critical way: it predates fzf's algorithm-v2 by several
# years (initial release 2012 by Kiro Risk; fzf v2 algorithm
# published 2017) and follows a *different* underlying
# scoring model based on Bitap-string-search with weighted
# field matching. The output rankings are close enough that
# users transferring from fzf to a fuse.js-backed UI don't
# notice the difference, but the algorithmic foundation is
# distinct. fuse.js's killer feature is the *weighted multi-
# field* search: each result item can be a structured object
# with multiple searchable fields, each weighted differently
# (e.g. title weight 0.7, body weight 0.3, tags weight 0.1).
# fzf-style matchers like nucleo / sahilm/fuzzy operate on
# flat strings only; matching structured records requires
# the caller to collapse them to a single key string first.
#
# Use-case alignment across the three lanes:
#   - purple (Rust, nucleo):     SSH host alias filtering -
#                                large flat string list
#   - nidhi (Go, sahilm/fuzzy):  git stash search - small
#                                flat string list
#   - deviceframe (Node, fuse.js): structured device records
#                                with brand+model+os+year
#                                fields, weighted matching
#
# The structural commentary: Axis 225's three lanes pick the
# matcher that best fits the *shape* of their data, not just
# the language. fzf-algorithm-v2 ports (nucleo, sahilm/fuzzy)
# dominate flat-list use cases; fuse.js dominates structured-
# record use cases - even within Node, fuzzy matchers like
# nexucis/fuzzy (closer to fzf-v2) coexist with fuse.js
# (closer to weighted-Bitap) because they target different
# problem shapes.
# ============================================================================

_deviceframe() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--delay[delay webpage capturing (seconds)]:seconds:' \
        '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'[output directory (default: CWD)]:dir:_files -/' \
        '(-d --debug)'{-d,--debug}'[log debug info]' \
        '--devices[list all available devices]' \
        '*--frame[supply a frame to use (fuzzy-matched; repeatable or comma-separated)]:frame:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '*:image file, image URL, or page URL:_files'
}

_deviceframe "$@"
